"# Chapter 1 — What composition is

Most tools that let you build a picture, a song, or a game keep two things separate: the tool and the thing the tool made. You open the tool. You drag some sliders. You click save. A file appears somewhere. Then you close the tool. Some other day you open the file in a text editor and stare at a wall of binary that means nothing. The tool remembered your work; the file remembered nothing you would recognize.

Motoi's composer refuses that separation. Every slider you drag, every note you place, every pixel you paint, every color you pick becomes a Scheme form. The file the composer saves is a normal `.slat` file with normal Scheme S-expressions inside it. Open it in a text editor and you see what you did. Open it back in the composer and the sliders sit where you left them. The file and the tool speak the same language.

This chapter is about the one property that makes the whole book work. It is the property Alfred kept naming until the composer got built: the round-trip.

## 1.1 The round-trip in one paragraph

You edit a widget. The widget mutates a Scheme form. You save the form to a `.slat` file. You quit the composer. You open the file in a text editor. You see the form. You edit the form by hand. You save. You reopen the file in the composer. The widget sits where the hand-edit put it. The tool did not lose your typing; the typing did not lose the tool.

Read that again. The composer does not have its own state. The file is the state. The widgets are a view of the file. Edits to the file update the widgets. Edits to the widgets update the file. Neither side is authoritative. Both sides read from and write to the same Scheme forms.

## 1.2 Why this matters

Consider what other composers do. A game engine's sprite editor stores pixels in a proprietary binary blob. Version control diffs are opaque. Two people cannot merge their edits. A music tracker stores patterns in binary. Copy-paste between tools is broken. A pixel art tool exports to PNG, but the file the tool opens next time is a project-format file only that tool understands. If the tool goes away, the work goes with it.

Motoi's composer files are text. Sprites are lists of palette indices. Music is lists of note records. Every widget declaration is a form you can read. If Motoi disappears tomorrow, your carts are still S-expressions, still parseable, still yours. The doctrine here is the same doctrine that put HTML in browsers instead of a proprietary binary: readable text outlasts the tool.

It matters for another reason too. When you can read the file, you can teach the file. A child learning to make a game can look at the .slat file the composer saved and say `oh, that is what I clicked`. The sprite the child painted is a list of numbers. The song the child arranged is a list of note forms. The composer is not a black box; it is a friendly translator between clicks and code.

There is a third reason and it is the one I care about most. When the file is text, other tools can read it. A batch script can crawl a directory of carts and rewrite every slider's `:max` field. A test harness can generate carts programmatically. A friend on a different operating system can open your file without your app installed. The composer is not an island. It is a small speaker in a much larger conversation, and the file is what everybody in that conversation is passing back and forth.

## 1.3 The two verbs at the heart of it

Two verbs make the round-trip explicit. Everything else in the composer is either a widget that participates in the round-trip or a helper that supports it.

`composer/emit` takes a canvas and returns the Scheme form the widgets currently compose. Move a slider, call `composer/emit`, get a form back. The form is what you would save to disk.

`composer/apply` takes a canvas and a form and mutates the widgets to reflect the form. Load a form from disk, call `composer/apply`, and the widgets update to match. Nothing is lost in either direction.

The mathematical statement:

```scheme
(composer/apply canvas (composer/emit canvas))  ;; ≡ canvas
```

Emit followed by apply is identity. This is the property tests verify. If it stops holding, the composer is broken.

Watch it work. Here is the smallest useful canvas — a slider bound to a BPM value:

```scheme
(define c
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/main))
    (composer/slider :label \"BPM\"
                     :bind '(cart/main :bpm)
                     :min 60 :max 240 :step 1)))

(composer/emit c)
;; => (composer/canvas (:bind (quote (cart/main)))
;;      (composer/slider :label \"BPM\" :bind (quote (cart/main :bpm))
;;                       :min 60 :max 240 :step 1 :value 60))
```

The emitted form is a `(composer/canvas ...)` declaration that includes the current value of every widget. Save this to disk, reload it, and the composer rebuilds a canvas whose slider knob sits at 60 — the value the emit preserved.

The output above was produced by `node bin/motoi eval` against the shipping runtime. Every code sample in this book was executed against `bin/motoi eval` before landing. That is the 1:1 promise: what the book says is what the runtime does. If you copy a code block out of this book, paste it into your terminal, and run it against `bin/motoi`, you get the same result the book shows. If not, the book is wrong. Not the runtime. Not you. The book. Please file a bug.

## 1.4 Widgets are Scheme values

Every widget verb returns a Scheme value — a record. `composer/slider` returns a slider record. `composer/button` returns a button record. `composer/canvas` returns a canvas record whose `:children` list holds the widget records passed as body forms.

Because widgets are values, you can hold them, name them, pass them, compose them:

```scheme
(define my-slider
  (composer/slider :label \"Volume\"
                   :bind '(mix :master)
                   :min 0.0 :max 1.0 :step 0.01))

(define my-canvas
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(mix))
    my-slider
    (composer/toggle :bind '(mix :muted) :label \"Muted\")))
```

That is exactly the syntax you use to build a canvas inline. Nothing special. Nothing hidden. A widget is a value; a canvas is a value; a canvas can contain any values a canvas expects.

This is different from most GUI builders you may have used. In an XML-based UI framework, you have a widget tree stored in XML and a code layer that talks to it through IDs. Motoi has neither. The widget IS the code. The tree IS the value. The value IS the file.

Think about the consequence for a moment. You can programmatically generate canvases. Here is a function that builds a slider bank for an arbitrary number of parameters:

```scheme
(define (slider-bank name params)
  (composer/canvas (list :bind (list name))
    (map (lambda (param)
           (composer/slider :label (symbol->string param)
                            :bind (list name param)
                            :min 0 :max 1 :step 0.01))
         params)))
```

Feed it `(slider-bank 'synth '(attack decay sustain release))` and it returns a canvas with four sliders, one per parameter, each bound to the right sub-slot. No template engine. No code generator. Just Scheme calling Scheme.

## 1.5 Bindings — the invisible thread

Every widget carries `:bind path`. The path is a list of symbols and keywords. It tells the composer where in the target form the widget's value lives.

Take a look at the slider example again:

```scheme
(composer/slider :label \"BPM\" :bind '(cart/main :bpm)
                 :min 60 :max 240 :step 1)
```

The bind path is `'(cart/main :bpm)`. That reads as: this slider owns the `:bpm` slot inside the top-level form named `cart/main`. Move the slider to 120, and the composer conceptually performs `(form-update '(cart/main :bpm) 120)` on the target. Emit the canvas, and the resulting form has `:bpm 120` in the right place.

Widgets do not know or care about each other. Two sliders bound to different paths cannot collide. Two sliders bound to the same path are legal and both update the same slot — the last one wins, which is what a human expects when two knobs claim to control the same parameter.

Bindings are symbolic. They do not carry index positions or DOM references. Rename `cart/main` to `song` and the widget's bind updates because you re-typed it, not because a magic proxy fixed it up. This is intentional. Symbolic paths let a human rename a form without breaking the widget graph, and let a widget survive a form reorganization if the target symbol stays put.

The path is a list because forms can nest. A slider bound to `'(synth :env :attack)` writes into the `:attack` slot inside the `:env` slot inside the `synth` top-level. Three levels deep. The path names them left to right, most-outer to most-inner. Kids parse this the same way they parse a folder path.

## 1.6 The canvas is the container

Every widget lives inside a canvas. The canvas has its own `:bind` — the root of the form the widgets collectively compose. Body forms passed after the `(:bind ...)` clause become children.

```scheme
(composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/main))
  (composer/slider :label \"BPM\" :bind '(cart/main :bpm)
                   :min 60 :max 240 :step 1)
  (composer/toggle :bind '(cart/main :muted) :label \"Muted\"))
```

The canvas here is bound to `'(cart/main)`. The two children own slots inside that form. Emit the canvas and you get one big `(composer/canvas ...)` declaration that carries both children's declarations, each with its current value baked in.

The composer accepts two spellings of the `:bind` clause. You can pass a `(list :bind '(cart/main))` as the first argument, or you can interleave `:bind` and its value directly in the argument list. Both parse to the same canvas. The examples in this book use the `(list :bind ...)` shape because it is unambiguous — the leading list marks the boundary between the canvas's own options and its children.

## 1.7 A first working example

Let me put the pieces together into something that runs. Save this as `carts/hello-composer.slat`:

```scheme
(define c
  (composer/canvas (list :bind '(cart/main))
    (composer/slider :label \"BPM\"
                     :bind '(cart/main :bpm)
                     :min 60 :max 240 :step 1)
    (composer/toggle :bind '(cart/main :muted) :label \"Muted\")))

(display (composer/emit c))
(newline)
(composer/apply c (composer/emit c))
(display \"round-trip ok\")
(newline)
```

Run it with `bin/motoi run carts/hello-composer.slat` and you see:

```
(composer/canvas (:bind (quote (cart/main)))
  (composer/slider :label \"BPM\" :bind (quote (cart/main :bpm))
                   :min 60 :max 240 :step 1 :value 60)
  (composer/toggle :bind (quote (cart/main :muted))
                   :label \"Muted\" :value #f))
round-trip ok
```

Two widgets. One canvas. One emitted form. `composer/apply` receives what `composer/emit` produced, does not throw, does not lose data. That is the whole promise, on the smallest possible surface, working the first time.

## 1.8 Zoom in on the emitted shape

Let me slow down and read the emit output one clause at a time, because if you understand this shape you understand every widget in the book. If you have been in code long enough that shapes-of-forms feel like second nature, you may skim. If not, please stay. This is where the round-trip stops being abstract and starts being obvious.

Start with the head:

```
(composer/canvas ...)
```

This says: the outer form is a canvas declaration. The `composer/canvas` verb, when re-evaluated later, will construct a canvas matching this shape.

Next the `:bind` clause:

```
(:bind (quote (cart/main)))
```

This is a list whose head is the `:bind` keyword. It sits at position one of the canvas form. The composer recognizes this shape and pulls the bind path out. `(quote (cart/main))` is the quoted form of the bind path — quoted so it does not evaluate as a call to `cart/main`.

Then the first child:

```
(composer/slider :label \"BPM\" :bind (quote (cart/main :bpm))
                 :min 60 :max 240 :step 1 :value 60)
```

That is a slider verb call. Every option shows up as a keyword–value pair. Notice `:value 60` at the end — that was NOT in the input form. The composer added it. The slider had no explicit `:value`, so it defaulted to `:min` (60). The emit captured the current state, so `:value 60` is now present. This is how round-trip preserves runtime state without asking the author to type it.

Then the toggle:

```
(composer/toggle :bind (quote (cart/main :muted)) :label \"Muted\" :value #f)
```

Same shape. Same pattern. `:value #f` because the toggle is off. Save this file, reload it, and the composer sees `:value #f` and instantiates the toggle in the off position. Round-trip.

Notice the pattern. Every widget declaration in the emit is:

```
(composer/KIND :keyword value :keyword value ...)
```

That is it. There is no envelope. There is no wrapper. There is no protocol. A widget declaration is a verb call whose arguments are keyword–value pairs. If you know how to call a Motoi verb, you know how to read a composer file.

## 1.9 Reading composer files in a text editor

Save the canvas above to a file and open it in your favorite editor. What you see is Scheme. It is grep-friendly. It is git-diff-friendly. It is the kind of text that survives — because it is text.

Try a hand edit. Change `:value 60` to `:value 140`. Save. Reload the file into the composer with `composer/load`. The slider's knob sits at 140. Nothing changed except a number in a text file.

Now try a subtler edit. Change `:max 240` to `:max 1000`. Save. Reload. The slider now accepts values up to 1000. The widget's option surface came from the file. You did not touch a settings panel; you did not open a preferences dialog; you edited a number, and the widget updated.

This is why the round-trip matters. It is not a party trick. It is the property that lets a person collaborate with a machine using text as the shared substrate. Git treats your composer file like it treats any source file. `diff` treats it like source. `grep` treats it like source. `sed`, though I would not recommend it for this, treats it like source. Every tool in the Unix pantheon inherited fifty years ago knows how to work with your composer file, because your composer file is text.

## 1.10 What round-trip does NOT promise

Honest about limits. The round-trip promises that emit-then-apply is identity for a single canvas. It does NOT promise:

- That two composers running against the same file merge cleanly at the same instant. That is a synchronization problem outside the round-trip; see the cross-surface engineering doc for the design.
- That every possible Scheme form you might hand-write is a valid canvas. If you hand-edit and remove a `:bind` from a slider, the composer accepts the form but the slider will not know where to write when you move it. Delete a whole `(composer/slider ...)` clause and the widget disappears.
- That widget-specific state that is not captured in the emit (say, in-progress drag position, hover state, animation timing) survives a save. It does not. Only committed state emits.
- That the emit and apply are cheap for huge canvases. A canvas with 10,000 widgets emits 10,000 declarations. If you build something that big you probably want to split it. Ordinary carts hold five to fifty widgets and the emit is instant.

Those limits are honest and small. They cover the edge cases; the core case — you edit, you save, you reopen, you see what you saved — works.

## 1.11 The four gestures a composer supports

Any composer widget supports four gestures in the round-trip contract:

1. Construct. `(composer/slider :label ... :bind ... :min ...)` — build a widget record from a plist.
2. Emit. `(composer/emit canvas)` — walk the widget tree, produce a Scheme form.
3. Apply. `(composer/apply canvas form)` — walk a Scheme form, mutate the widget tree.
4. Save + load. `(composer/save canvas path)` and `(composer/load path)` — the emit and apply plus file I/O.

Every subsequent chapter introduces a new widget kind, but each widget participates in these same four gestures. Learn the gestures once; every widget joins the pattern.

## 1.12 Widgets are Scheme authors

There is an old idea in Lisp culture that the reader for the language should be the same reader an author uses to serialize data. Scheme took that to heart with S-expressions: code and data have the same shape. Motoi's composer takes it one step further: widgets and forms have the same shape too.

A slider is not a class instance whose fields are secret; it is a Scheme record whose emission is a Scheme form. A canvas is not a document with a DOM; it is a form that contains other forms. When a widget writes, it writes Scheme. When the reader reads, it reads Scheme back into widgets. There is no impedance mismatch to fix. There is no serializer to write. There is only the round-trip.

Once you internalize this, you stop thinking of the composer as a UI-with-a-backing-store. You start thinking of it as a set of verbs whose values happen to render nicely as widgets on the surfaces that know how to render them. That is closer to the truth. A canvas is a value. A slider is a value. A piano-roll is a value. What you see on screen is a rendering the surface chose to give you, but the value itself has no visual identity; the value only has a shape and a bound path.

## 1.13 Where surfaces come in

If widgets are pure Scheme values, who draws them?

Different surfaces. The Curator canvas draws them as visible sliders and grids and buttons. The TUI (see Chapter 14) draws them as ASCII in a terminal. The HTTP server (see Chapter 15) serves them in a browser. A test harness needs no rendering at all; it just constructs canvases, moves widgets programmatically via helper verbs, and checks the emit.

The verbs do not know which surface will render them. The composer is deterministic. Slider moves become numbers. Button clicks become forms. Piano-roll cell clicks become notes. All pure. All translatable to any surface that speaks Motoi.

## 1.14 What Sakura is doing in all of this

Nothing, unless you ask. The composer runs offline. No model in the loop. A kid on a plane with no network can compose. A composer session that never speaks to Sakura is a complete, working, useful composer session.

You CAN invite Sakura into a session. `(copilot/ask ...)` and friends live alongside composer verbs and can rewrite an emitted form, propose a palette, critique a song. But every widget works without her, and that is by design. The composer's guarantee is deterministic. Sakura's guarantee is a helpful hedge. Two different guarantees. Two different jobs.

## 1.15 A brief tour of what is coming

Chapter 2 goes deep on `composer/canvas` — the container, the binding-path model, how canvases nest, how children get discovered.

Chapters 3 and 4 cover the two atomic input widgets: the slider (numbers) and the button-plus-toggle pair (events and flags). These are the two building blocks every other widget is a variation on.

Chapters 5 through 8 walk the media widgets: piano-roll for note sequences, sprite grid for pixel data, tile map for layered levels, timeline for animation. Each has an emit shape distinctive to its domain and each honors the round-trip.

Chapters 9 and 10 cover sound shaping — ADSR envelopes, instrument pickers, FX chains. This is where you learn how a widget composes a Scheme form that the audio engine plays.

Chapter 11 covers text field, color picker, and the live-code widget — the widget whose sole purpose is to expose the emit-and-apply loop as a scrollable text panel a human can edit directly. If Chapter 1 introduces the round-trip, Chapter 11 shows the round-trip in a window.

Chapter 12 introduces the 16-voice mixer that composer v1.1 added. Chapter 13 covers save-and-load — what a .slat file actually looks like, what round-trip preserves, what it does not. Chapter 14 covers the TUI mode where the composer runs in a terminal. Chapter 15 covers the HTTP server that publishes a cart so a friend can play it. Chapter 16 walks a full worked example — sprite plus sound plus tile-map plus HTTP publish plus friend plays.

Then eight appendices: verb reference, ASCII mockup gallery, emit-shape catalog, five worked round-trip proofs, the HTML-16 palette catalog, ten voice mixing recipes, a TUI cheat-sheet, and the HTTP server security guide.

That is the whole book. It is a book about one property (the round-trip) and fifteen verbs (the composer surface) and a lot of little demonstrations of how those fifteen verbs, honoring that one property, produce something a child can master.

## 1.16 The doctrine, one more time

Sliders don't have opinions. Buttons don't have opinions. Every widget is bound to a path. Moving the widget mutates the form. Emitting the canvas returns the form. Applying a form to the canvas updates the widgets. Save produces a `.slat` file. Load reconstructs the widgets. Nothing between the widget and the file is proprietary. Nothing between the file and the widget is lossy.

That is the whole doctrine. Every remaining chapter is a study of one widget or one operation applied against it. You will meet sliders in depth, buttons and toggles, piano-rolls, sprite grids, tile maps, timelines, ADSR envelopes, instrument pickers, FX chains, text fields, color pickers, and the live-code widget that closes the loop. You will meet the 16-voice mixer. You will meet the TUI mode where the composer runs in a terminal. You will meet the HTTP publish flow. You will meet a full worked example — a small game composed from sprites, sounds, tiles, and a link a friend can play.

None of it is complicated once the round-trip is clear. Everything is a variation on: move a thing, get a form, save the form, reload the form, see the thing where you left it.

## 1.17 One more small verified demonstration

Before the chapter ends I want to give you one more piece of verified output, because I have been asking you to trust that the runtime does what the book says, and I would rather show it than ask you to trust.

Take the two-widget canvas from earlier. Save it to disk with `composer/save`:

```scheme
(composer/save c \"/tmp/hello.slat\")
```

The return value is the string `\"/tmp/hello.slat\"`. Now look at the file:

```
(composer/canvas (:bind (quote (cart/main)))
  (composer/slider :label \"BPM\" :bind (quote (cart/main :bpm))
                   :min 60 :max 240 :step 1 :value 60)
  (composer/toggle :bind (quote (cart/main :muted))
                   :label \"Muted\" :value #f))
```

Now reload it:

```scheme
(composer/load \"/tmp/hello.slat\")
```

You get a canvas record back, with two children — a slider and a toggle. Emit that canvas and you get the same form the file held. The round-trip closed over disk.

This is not clever plumbing. It is `formatForm` writing Scheme text, then the reader parsing Scheme text, then the constructor rebuilding widgets from the parsed forms. The same primitives you use every day handle it.

## 1.18 What to remember from this chapter

- The composer's file format is Scheme. No binary blobs. No proprietary schemas.
- Every widget is a value. `composer/slider` returns a slider record.
- Every widget carries `:bind path`. The path names where in the target form the widget's value lives.
- Every widget lives inside a canvas. The canvas is a container with its own `:bind`.
- `composer/emit` produces a Scheme form from a canvas. `composer/apply` updates a canvas from a form. Emit-then-apply is identity.
- `composer/save` and `composer/load` extend the round-trip to disk.
- The composer is deterministic. No model in the loop. A kid on a plane with no network can compose.
- Every code sample in this book was verified against `bin/motoi eval` before landing. What the book says is what the runtime does.

Chapter 2 introduces `composer/canvas` in depth — how it composes, how it nests, how bindings resolve, and how the emitted form is structured when a canvas holds many children.
")
